[Scene 1 | 0–3s]
"What if you could compress an image down to just 32 numbers… and rebuild it perfectly? Autoencoders do exactly this. Crazy."

[Scene 2 | 3–13s]
"Here's how it works. You feed an image into an Encoder — a neural network that squeezes it down into just 32 numbers. That tiny vector is called the latent space."

[Scene 3 | 13–23s]
"Then a Decoder takes those 32 numbers and expands them back into the full image. Input goes in. Reconstruction comes out."

[Scene 4 | 23–33s]
"How does it learn? Simple. Compare the input to the reconstruction. Minimize the difference. No labels needed — the image IS the label. That's unsupervised learning."

[Scene 5 | 33–42s]
"The bottleneck is the secret. With only 32 numbers, the encoder is forced to learn only the most important features — shape, color, structure. Everything else gets dropped."

[Scene 6 | 42–50s]
"This unlocks powerful applications: anomaly detection, image denoising, and data compression. Normal inputs reconstruct cleanly. Anomalies don't."

[Scene 7 | 50–57s]
"The latent space is pure magic. Interpolate between two faces in latent space and they morph smoothly. This idea became the foundation of Stable Diffusion."

[Scene 8 | 57–60s]
